Data Science and Global Warming: A Closer Look at Rising Temperatures¶

Kyla Perkinson, Fall 2022¶

Introduction¶

Motivation¶

Climate change has been a concern for decades, yet within recent years there has been a dramatic politicization of the topic. Despite overwhelming evidence of it and its detrimental impacts on the planet, many continue to deny the existence of climate change or downplay its significance. I decided to do my project on increasing global temperatures and possible causes of it because I believe that the data can speak for itself. I hope to provide a clear and objective look at the reality of increasing temperatures on our planet. I believe that looking at the data is the first step to moving past the political debates surrounding the existence of climate change and will lead to more productive conversations about the policies that must be put in place to prevent this climate crisis from worsening.

This project specifically looks at how year, continent, and carbon dioxide emissions have an impact on global temperatures. I chose to look at carbon dioxide because according to the United States Environmental Protection Agency, carbon dioxide has significantly higher emission levels than all other greenhouse gases. At this end of this tutorial, you will be able to collect and process data, analyze data trends using an assortment of visualizations, and create predictive models using linear and polynomial regression.

What does this look like on a map?¶

I have looked at the temperature change globally and by continent, and now I want to break it down further by looking at the temperature change by country. First, I need to calculate how much the temperature has changed in each country between 1901 and 2021. To do that, I am going to create a new data frame, country_temp_change, which will have a row for each country and a column for how much the temperature has changed between 1901 and 2021. To calculate that change for each country, I am going to take the temperature values from temperatures for each country in 1901 and 2021 and find the difference, then add this to country_temp_change.

In [1016]:
# Adding all the country names from global_temp to the new dataframe country_temp_change
countries = temperatures["Country"].unique()
country_temp_change = pd.DataFrame(countries, columns=["Country"])
temp_change = list()

# Calculating how much the temperature has changed between 1901 and 2021 for each country
for country in countries:
    temp_1901 = temperatures.loc[temperatures["Country"] == country, "Temperature"].iloc[0]
    temp_2021 = temperatures.loc[temperatures["Country"] == country, "Temperature"].iloc[-1]
    temp_change.append(temp_2021 - temp_1901)
country_temp_change["Temperature Change"] = temp_change
country_temp_change.head()

map_osm = folium.Map(location=[0, 0], zoom_start=2)

cp = folium.Choropleth(

# Adding a tooltip to show country name and adding it to the map
folium.GeoJsonTooltip(['name'], ['Country:']).add_to(cp.geojson)
folium.LayerControl().add_to(map_osm)

This boxplot shows some of the same insights the map did. The green line is the average temperature change in each continent, and it shows that Europe and Asia had the highest average temperature change, which matches the analysis from the map. It also looks like there are a few outliers for the Americas, Oceania, and Africa, and I am curious to see what they are.

matplotlib defines its outliers as points that are more than 1.5 times the interquartile range above the upper quartile and below the lower quartile, so outliers < Q1 - 1.5 IQR and outliers > Q3 + 1.5 IQR. I am going to use these bounds to find the outliers in the dataset.

In [1020]:
# Creating an outliers DataFrame
outliers = pd.DataFrame()

# Find the outliers for each continent by finding the temperature changes that are < Q1 - 1.5 * IQR and > Q3 + 1.5 * IQR and adding them to the outliers DataFrame
for continent in continents:
    continent_temp_change = country_temp_change[country_temp_change["Continent"] == continent].copy()
    q1, q3 = np.percentile(continent_temp_change["Temperature Change"], [25, 75])
    iqr = q3 - q1
    lower = q1 - (1.5 * iqr)
    upper = q3 + (1.5 * iqr)
    outliers = outliers.append(continent_temp_change[(continent_temp_change["Temperature Change"] < lower) | (continent_temp_change["Temperature Change"] > upper)]);

outliers.head(10)

Looking at the drastic differences in carbon dioxide emissions for each continent is making me want to look further into individual country carbon dioxide emissions. I want to see if the countries follow the same trends as their respective continents, or if there are significant outliers that are causing such drastic differences in carbon dioxide emissions by continent. To do this, I am going to make another choropleth map using folium.

This choropleth map is going to the average yearly increase in carbon dioxide emissions for each country. First, I am going to create a new dataframe, country_co2_change, which will have a row for each country and a column to show each country's average change in carbon dioxide emissions each year, measured in million tonnes per year. To get this value, I am finding the total change in carbon dioxide emissions for each country and dividing it by the number of years the country's carbon dioxide emissions are recorded.

In [1025]:
# Creating a new dataframe that has a row for each country in greenhouse_gases
countries = greenhouse_gases["Country"].unique()
country_co2_change = pd.DataFrame(countries, columns=["Country"])
co2_change = list()

# Finding the average change in carbon dioxide emissions for each country and adding it to the new dataframe
for country in countries:
    num_years = len(greenhouse_gases.loc[(greenhouse_gases["Country"] == country), "CO2"])
    co2_early = greenhouse_gases.loc[(greenhouse_gases["Country"] == country), "CO2"].iloc[0]
    co2_late = greenhouse_gases.loc[(greenhouse_gases["Country"] == country), "CO2"].iloc[-1]
    co2_change.append((co2_late - co2_early) / num_years)                     
country_co2_change["CO2 Change"] = co2_change
country_co2_change.head()

Using the same process as before, I am creating a new dataframe, outliers, and adding rows to it that have average yearly carbon dioxide emissions that are more than 1.5 times the interquartile range above the upper quartile or below the lower quartile.

In [1028]:
# Creating an outliers dataframe
outliers = pd.DataFrame()

# Finding the outliers for each continent by finding the carbon dioxide changes that are < Q1 - 1.5 * IQR and > Q3 + 1.5 * IQR and adding them to the outliers dataframe
for continent in continents:
    continent_co2_change = country_co2_change[country_co2_change["Continent"] == continent].copy()
    q1, q3 = np.percentile(continent_co2_change["CO2 Change"], [25, 75])
    iqr = q3 - q1
    lower = q1 - (1.5 * iqr)
    upper = q3 + (1.5 * iqr)
    outliers = outliers.append(continent_co2_change[(continent_co2_change["CO2 Change"] < lower) | (continent_co2_change["CO2 Change"] > upper)]);

# Sort the dataframe by 'CO2 Change' in descending orders
outliers = outliers.sort_values(by=['CO2 Change'], ascending=False)
outliers.head(5)

Multiple Regression¶

From preliminary analysis and visualization, it appears that year and global carbon dioxide emissions interact to affect global temperatures. To further explore this, I want to use this last section to create a multiple regression model that can predict global temperature based on year and carbon dioxide emissions.

First I need to determine if I should use linear regression or polynomial regression of degree two. To do so, I am going to see which degree has the lowest root mean square error by creating models for both and comparing the average root mean square error. Root mean square error is a metric used to determine the accuracy of a model, and three other common metrics are mean square error, r square, and mean absolute error. I am choosing to use root mean square error because it is a weighted average that is penalized more for larger prediction errors, and it uses same units as the predicted variable, which in this case is degree celsius.

To create the model, I am first defining the variables and then creating the new features based on the degree of the model. Creating new features means creating necessary variables based on the polynomial degree. For example, for the multiple polynomial regression in degree two, the formula looks like:

**y = B0 + B1x1 + B2x2 + B3x12 + B4x22 + B5x1x2**

For a degree of two, the new features would be x12, x22, x1x2, etc, where x1 = year and x2 = carbon dioxide emissions. Then the polynomial features and y values are going to split into testing and training data so that model can be tested on data it has never seen before after being trained. Now that this is done, the model is ready to be created. Even though we are creating a polynomial regression, it is still a form of linear regression, and therefore LinearRegression() is going to be used on the polynomial features that were created. Then we are going to fit the model to the training data and use the testing data to find the predicted y values, in this case predicted temperatures. Lastly, the root mean square error is going to be calculated using the predicted and testing y values, and this will be added to an array to keep track of the degree and root mean square for each model. To create the linear regression model, the polynomial features will not be created, but the data will also be split into training and testing data to fit the model and find the predicted temperatures once the model has been trained.

I am going to start by creating the linear regression model.

In [1033]:
# Declaring the x and y variables
X = global_temps_gases[["Year", "CO2"]]
y = global_temps_gases["Temperature"]
In [1034]:
# Splitting the data into training and testing data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# Creating and fitting the model
lin_model = LinearRegression()
lin_model = lin_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Finding the predicted temperatures and calculating the root mean square error
y_predicted = lin_model.predict(X_test)
lin_rmse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_predicted, squared=False)

print(f'The root mean square error of the linear regression model is {round(lin_rmse, 4)}, which means that on average, each prediction is incorrect by about {round(lin_rmse, 4)} degrees celsius.')

The root mean square error of the linear regression model is 0.1865, which means that on average, each prediction is incorrect by about 0.1865 degrees celsius.
In [1035]:
# Creating the polynomial features
poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2, include_bias=False)
poly_features = poly.fit_transform(X)
    
# Splitting the data into training and testing data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(poly_features, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# Creating and fitting the model
poly_model = LinearRegression()
poly_model = poly_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
# Finding the predicted temperatures and calculating the root mean square error
y_predicted = poly_model.predict(X_test)
poly_rmse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_predicted, squared=False)

print(f'The root mean square error of the linear regression model is {round(poly_rmse, 4)}, which means that on average, each prediction is incorrect by about {round(poly_rmse, 4)} degrees celsius.')   

The root mean square error of the linear regression model is 0.1337, which means that on average, each prediction is incorrect by about 0.1337 degrees celsius.

Comparing the root mean square of these two models shows that the on average, the polynomial regression's predicted temperatures are closer than those the the linear regression model. This means the polynomial regressoin model fits the dataset the best. Therefore, it is the model I will be using to predict the temperature based on year and carbon dioxide emissions.

To visualize how this regression compares to the actual temperatures, it can be graphed on the same plot.

In [1036]:

Predicting future temperatures¶

Now that I have a predictive model for temperature based on year and carbon dioxide emissions, I want to predict the temperature for future years. I will be using carbon dioxide emission predictions from the Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development's Environmental Outlook to 2050. According to this document, it is predicted that carbon dioxide emissions will be about 42,000 million tonnes in 2030, 47,000 million tonnes in 2040, and 55,000 million tonnes in 2050. I will be using these carbon dioxide projections to use the model to determine the predicted global temperature through 2050.

To do so, I am first adding three new rows with the predicted carbon dioxide emissions for 2030, 2040, and 2050. I will then create polynomial features from this and use the model to predict the temperatures based on the year and projected carbon dioxide emissions. To visualize these predicted temperatures, I am going to graph them with the actual temperatures.

In [1038]:
# Creating a new dataframe with year and carbon dioxide emissions and adding the projected carbon dioxide emissions to it
co2_predictions = X
co2_predictions = co2_predictions.append({'Year' : 2030, 'CO2' : 42000}, ignore_index=True)
co2_predictions = co2_predictions.append({'Year' : 2040, 'CO2' : 47000}, ignore_index=True)
co2_predictions = co2_predictions.append({'Year' : 2050, 'CO2' : 55000}, ignore_index=True)

# Creating polynomial features and using them to find the model's predictions
poly_features = poly.fit_transform(co2_predictions)
y_predicted = poly_model.predict(poly_features)

# Plotting the current and projected temperatures
plt.plot(global_temps_gases["Year"], global_temps_gases["Temperature"], color="#94dd9d", label="Actual")
plt.plot(co2_predictions["Year"], y_predicted, color="#3a4d89", label="Predicted")
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("Temperature (celsius)")
plt.title("Global Temperature Projections");
plt.legend();

According to the model, the temperature is expected to increase by about 1.5 degrees celsius by 2050. This may seem small, but its actually a pretty big concern. The National Center for Science Education has published this article explaining why this increase is so significant.

Insight & Next Steps¶

Insight¶

Throughout this project, a few trends have become evident:

  • temperatures and carbon dioxide emissions have been increasing exponentially since 1901
  • the change in temperature annually across continents is similar, yet the change in carbon dioxide across continents varies
  • there is a positive correlation between temperature change and carbon dioxide emissions
  • the global change in average temperature fluctuates significantly more than the global change in carbon dioxide emissions
  • a several countries have significantly higher carbon dioxide emissions than the rest of the world

What can I do to help stop global warming?¶

Everyone can play a part in stopping global warming! Here is a list of changes to daily habits that everyone can do to help protect our planet:

  • Eat less meat
  • Turn off lights and appliances when they aren't in use
  • Carpool or take public transportation
  • Use reusable water bottles, plastic containers, and shopping bags
  • Buy clothes second-hand and donate clothes you no longer want
  • Use towels and rags instead of paper towels

Lastly, you can calculate your carbon footprint using The Nature Conservancy's Carbon Footprint Calculator and get suggestions on how to decrease it.

This tutorial was just a glimpse at one of the many manmade causes of global warming. There are many other variables to look at regarding climate change, such as deforestation, other greenhouse gases, and population growth. With the information provided in this tutorial, you now have the tools needed for any further analysis that intrigues you!
